Title: Run Your Mouth
Comment:
"That you only hold me when I'm on my knees" 

"Got me so tied up, when you push my luck"

Title: Keep Riding Me
Comment: It took me so long to find this song, it was buried in some playlist where I’d only hear it once a year or so to truly sip it like a fine wine

Title: STAR
Comment: The vibe of this song is all “yeah, I’m the shit” until Kevin Abstract hops on for the third verse and starts talking about sucking dick. It’s a really unexpected pivot that makes me chuckle every time

Title: You Think You're A Man
Comment: Flash back to middle school. You’re listening to Kurt Cobain’s favorite band play a cover of a Divine tune in your mom’s car. The song is a jauntily little lo-fi dance tune with some kinda horny lyrics but then the bridge comes on and your mom has to listen to The Vaselines moan in with orgasmic satisfaction while you awkwardly try to slip to the next track.

Title: Animals
Comment: Nickleback gets a lot of hate, partially because it's popular to hate them and partially because their music is unoriginal, formulaic, buttrock. But did you know that the meme-famous "Photograph" is immediately followed on the album by this confusingly horny song? What was the mood like in the studio while Chad Kroger sang about having sex in a car with someone the lyrics suggest was a minor?

Title: Of All The Gin Joints In All The World
Comment: A solid 75% of early Fall Out Boy songs fit in this category, but I feel like this is the best fit of all of them

Title: Annie's Song
Comment: For what should be a lovely sincere love song to his wife, there was no need for Denver to make this so ridiculously horny. No one needs this amount of vivid horny imagery for a married couple. I am absolutely not denying it as a beautiful song but my god Denver please stop asking to be filled up

Title: H.W.C.
Comment: Even by Liz Phair standards, this one always seemed like a bit much. (“Flower,” in contrast, is NECESSARILY horny.) Fun and catchy, though!

Title: Welcome To My Island - George Daniel & Charli XCX Remix
Artist(s): Caroline Polachek, Charli xcx, George Daniel
Comment:
The original song is not exactly horny. Caroline says “It’s really about ego at its core—about being trapped in your own head and forcing everyone else in there with you” and mentions her dad in the bridge. 

This remix has some over the top additions. The first bit from Charli on this version fits right in with the ego theme, but then it gets so horny. This is my ultimate car song, but I feel a little shy showing other people with “legs wide out like banana split” and “be a good girl” etc

Title: Murphy Bed
Album: You Think It's Like This But Really It's Like This
Comment:
This could easily be just another sad long-distance love song, sprinkled with some euphemism or innuendo… but Mirah throws in some clear-as-day horny lyrics. 

"Tie me to the murphy bed / Let's do all the things you said"

I'm sure a lot of songwriters would think this unnecessary, but makes it way more memorable.

Title: Hold Me, Thrill Me, Kiss Me, Kill Me - From 'Batman Forever'
Comment: I don’t like U2. But I love this song. But why does Bono need to come his brains out at the end? This is why I don’t like U2. Because Bono.

Title: Lord Of The Thighs
Comment:
Aerosmith songs are all unnecessarily horny, and should only be listened to if they are being covered by a well-spoken but deadpan English lesbian bass player (Josephine Wiggs) doing an extremely rare lead vocal for the Breeders.

The original is super creepy and has a terrible pun for a title, but the Breeders find a way to make it great.

Title: Add It Up
Comment: Amazing song! Super horny song! And fuck “unnecessary”! Let the people be horny! We don’t have enough horny songs!

Title: Today's Lesson
Comment:
Funky rock song from Nick Cave then a couple of verses in-
Mr Sandman, he has a certain appetite for Janie in repose
He digs her pretty knees and that she is completely naked underneath all her clothes
He likes to congregate around the intersection of Janie's jeans yeah
Mr Sandman the inseminator he opens her up like a love letter and enters her dreams

Title: Re-Make/Re-Model
Comment: Man, that sax solo. Or should I say... that sex solo! OK, I'm done, forget me forever now.

Title: Mahal
Comment: Just going for some nice background music, nothing disruptive to conversations being had. But Glass Beams is hella groovy, catchy, and well-produced. I’m so nervous, the cool kids never invite me to their parties.

Title: Bleed It Out
Comment: The theme specifies for a party, and this is really just a great party song for dancing and having a good time to.

Title: Don't You Forget
Comment: This is a party where we drink cocktails while swaying among the lights strung across someone’s backyard on a warm summer evening. Everyone is beautiful but approachable and interesting because they’re musicians, artists, and writers. They all ask what this song is because it’s just so cool.

Title: Ahead By A Century
Comment: I think I would play this trying to be cool. But as I am in fact not cool I think I would just bum everyone out

Title: The Largest
Comment: The perfect party banger is a rap song where everyone can feel the vibe, even if they’ve never heard it before. This dude reminds me of Biggie, but he was pretty much unknown until last year, so it scores cool points too.

Title: Tacoma Black Party - Live
Comment: I think this song is super cool. I love this band. There’s a longer version of this on Loveland but I’ll pick the shorter here to be merciful. Just a really cool song that wails.
This person was on SNL recently and they only have cool musicians

Title: Deceptacon
Comment: I think this combo might be it. DIY punk and riot grrrl cred mixed with electro cool. Some people will know it, some won’t, but it’ll get everyone dancing.

Title: Wrapped In Gold
Comment:
Izzy Camina is cool, and now I am slightly cooler for telling you about her. You can also become slightly cooler by telling other people about her, it's like a coolness pyramid scheme.

She wrote and completely self-produced this track, and the EP it's from. And you can dance to it - it's not the kind of cool that bums everyone out at the party.

Title: Around the World / Harder, Better, Faster, Stronger
Comment:
Came up with a hundred songs that were all very party-dependent. House party? Child’s birthday party? Party to a federal crime?

In the end it doesn’t matter. More people need to be aware of Alive 2007 and the aux cord beatings will continue until appreciation improves

Title: No Woman, No Cry - Live At The Lyceum, London/1975
Album: Legend - The Best Of Bob Marley And The Wailers
Comment: "Yeah you know this song but this is the best version. Live in 1975 in London, this is the definitive version of a reggae classic. Please think I'm cool."

Title: Middle Man
Album: Everything Is Possible: The Very Best of Living Colour
Comment:
It's a sound that'll work for a party, but is also likely stand out from the rest of what's playing. Living Colour strikes a great balance where enough people will know them to back me up when I go "oh, you haven't heard?" but enough people won't know them that I'll get to go "oh, you haven't heard?" in the first place.

Plus I get to one-up the people who are like "oh the Cult of Personality band" in just the cruelest way. I'll have to make sure not to be the first to name drop CM Punk, though.

Title: dream
Comment: Depending on the crowd, some folks might find this kind of cool - I designed the album art for this mixtape.

Title: Red Wine Supernova
Album: The Rise and Fall of a Midwest Princess
Comment: Everyone would be screaming every lyric at any party this comes on, this is easy cool points

Title: Big
Comment: Well if I'm at a cool party (I'm thinking it's college cool and it's a party of people doing a cooler course than me like Film Studies and they all dress cool and smoke) I'm going to have to divert my thinking to my younger brother Daniel who has always been cooler than me. You may already know Fontaines D.C. as the next big band coming from Ireland but this is Daniel's favourite song from them and it's from when they were just starting out. We play it when we drive around in his new car

Title: Bloom
Comment:
Sean! I know you like Garbage, and I feel like you've either submitted or at least upvoted CHVRCHES, so maybe you'll like some more indie-electro sung by an audibly-Scottish lady? 

Helen Marnie is the lead singer of Ladytron (who you may know from the Liverpool connection, or from them just being Ladytron). Her solo stuff has been kind of slept on (just 2% of the listeners of her main band), but I think this whole album is just a little bit better & more fun than anything Ladytron have released

Title: Killing Birds With Stones
Comment:
I got Scott Murray

Research: He said in an entry in league 20 that his AOTY in 2023 was TesseracT, and he's a fan of prog metal. His slack profile mentions he's a drummer.

Analysis: I searched reddit for recommendations of prog metal bands with noteworthy drummers and picked the recommendation with the fewest listeners on Spotify. 

Conclusion: Intronaut only has 16.6k monthly listeners, so there's at least a  possibility that this is new to you. It's their most popular song so hopefully it's

Title: Flowers To My Demons
Comment:
For: Sam

I wouldn't be too surprised if you're on Nnamdi Ogbonnaya already but I think he's super cool, and hits some of the same stylistic points as some of your submissions. The section at 1:26 is especially fun. Hope you enjoy

Title: Run to Your Shelters
Comment: This song is a gift for Mac! My research shows that like many legendary HT writers, you are a fan of classic 90s-era punk. St. Plaster’s whole deal, per their bio, is bringing back that old-school style. Reviews called their 2019 debut album “loud, fast, and bratty” and compared them to early Rancid, Green Day, and Bad Religion. Can’t say if all the comparisons are fully deserved quite yet, but their single here is nicely angry and pretty great overall. I hope you enjoy! 🛹

Title: Strawberry Milkshake
Comment: The name I drew was Alex Kitsinger.  After looking through past entries of Alex's, there was a common thread of punk rock and rock. So there's this band called Bad Waitress, they've been around for a couple years, but this album is really good. I dig it a lot. It's punky/riot grrl with a twist of oddities in there and for my money, it's a really cool combination. This is my fave song on the album. So merry Xmas, Alex! I hope you enjoy!

Title: H.Y.C.Y.BH
Comment: Bob Kerr picked a Weird Al song for his feel better round so went with that and offered up another incredible parody song

Title: A More Perfect Union
Comment:
Hey Bex! Happy holidays and merry end of 2024 and Santa secret song day. I hope whatever you do in the next week or so is awesome and relaxing.

Realized the Venn diagram of our music tastes had a larger nougaty core than I expected! Jeff Rosenstock, Bayside, I saw you commenting about The Menzingers.

Started listening to John-Allison Weiss and Living Colour after you posted them and I really dig it!

Out of chars - this is one of my all-time faves, I think you may dig & hope you havent heard!

Title: Black Coffee
Comment: I drew James Knapp and I got him the “James Knappiest” Christmas gift I could find - a Black Flag banger. Merry Christmas man! 💕

Title: Velvet Ring - 2023 Remaster
Comment: This just seemed like a song that Patrick would enjoy

Title: Indian Grits
Comment:
I got the new guy, so this is the hardest one. Vote accordingly.

Based on extensive research, it seems like you spend way too much time in the worlds of Phish and Limp Bizkit. I’m hoping this means you’re genuinely a jam band guym and not just hate-watching everything. Either way, here’s ‘Indian Grits’ by Dopapod—enjoy it, or admit you’ve gone too deep

Title: Cum on Feel the Noize
Comment: Jesslil is cool, hosted a college radio show, and dominated the first round with a song about Hot, White, Cum. I feel like this song checks off everything I know about her.

Title: Rocky Took A Lover
Comment:
For Matt McInerney. You like The Weakerthans, Wafflehouse*, Breaking Pangea, and Taylor Swift.
So what I know is lyrics are important to you. And you like music that will bum you out. It's great to feel emotions through music. I also know you are clever and extremely talented in the world of computer engineering. My instinct is to send you The National, but you probably have an opinion on them. So I wanted to bring you a song by a band who have incredible lyrics and a sound I think you'll like

Title: Fine, Great
Comment: I got Jacob Brefka, and between them submitting a Front Bottoms song and giving off very strong midwest vibes I am quite confident they are either already a fan of Mobo, or would like them if they gave them a shot.

Title: Hold Me
Comment: The challenge to choose a song for Ciara was apparent from the beginning. Seeing an affinity for both John Denver and Mvll Crimes I can see that personality and humor in a lyric goes a long way. José Suicidio is a product of comedian Henry Phillips (of Henry’s Kitchen, You and Your F*ing Coffee, etc) and it represents a commitment to a joke beyond simply the lyrics. It fits the season of diminished sunlight. The rest of the album is great but this song stands out to me. New favorite banger?

Title: Little Black Backpack - Remastered
Comment: I got Bubble as my pick, and it is taking all of my willpower to not just do Eve 6. So instead, here's Stroke 9. They have a kind of similar vibe to Eve 6, and while this song is well known they aren't like mega-popular. Plus 9 is a whole three numbers higher than 6, so if that doesn't speak to the quality I don't know what will. I think you'll dig it

Title: Chewed up and Spit out (In a Bowl)
Comment: I don't think anyone has submitted Algernon Cadwallader before. We need some more Midwest emo around here.

Title: Nazi Punks Fuck Off
Album: Plastic Surgery Disasters/In God We Trust, Inc.
Comment: Always apt.

Title: Sublime Sun Tattoo
Album: I Know Now Why You Cry
Comment: Play it safe, Jason, don’t weird them out. Just go for this gorgeous Gregory Pepper track. Don’t overthink it. People want to enjoy their playlists.

Title: HUMANOID / SHAKE IT UP
Comment: Love this album so much - nice meaty song for just over a minute

Title: Beach Community
Comment:
In 2013 my roommates and I hosted some visiting hooligans and paid them in free pints of PBR for a backyard house show. In March 2020 I caught them playing at a brewery in Denver then went to a Bernie rally with them after 

The world shut down the next day, and I woke up the following with a 103 fever. In a different reality I’d like to think we would’ve synced back up but instead I nearly went to the hospital lol

Such is life

Title: Die Mad
Comment: This is a nice, loud, angry, 90-second song from one of my favorite albums of this year. Highly recommend the whole record if y'all are into emo bullshit

Title: Body
Comment: Can't believe I've never submitted Magdalena Bay before, but better late than never

Title: United States Of Whatever
Comment:
My wife loves this song, and they are rarely wrong.
Also, when i pick them up from work their coworkers call me "Himothy Chalomet" which is not a detail you need to know but thought I would share it anyway.

Title: Braintrust
Comment: I was obsessed with this album for a minute. I’m glad I got to see them live before Rick died.

Title: Unity 〜パピーとの再会
Comment: challenge: close your eyes and make yourself just listen to this song and be alone with your thoughts for a whole minute. Almost impossible for some of us, but a worthy micro-journey! And a good song in any case

Title: Juicebox Baby
Comment: This song has been stuck in my head for years and I sing the chorus several times a week with my kids at lunch/snack time

Title: A Place Where Love Goes
Album: Bando Stone and The New World
Comment:
I’m a sucker for (almost) everything that Donald Glover puts out. When he announced that Bando Stone would be his final album AND his next movie I RAN (not walked) to listen to it. I was not disappointed by the album, but I am VERY disappointed by the movie… as it seems increasingly likely that the “trailer” that dropped was just a marketing stunt for the album (tldr: movie likely isn’t real). 

The chorus of APWLG gives me chills - my fav track on the my fav album of the year!

Title: Weird Ending Explained, Pt. 1
Comment: this song is probably a little better in the context of the album, but is still a great multi-part, eight minute track that stays interesting the whole time

Title: Bury
Comment: A lot of my favorite songs from last year would probably fall under “super obvious,” so here’s a spooky heavy-dreamy doom/shoegaze sorta song that was also excellent. It’s from a soundtrack for an A24 film which I believe makes me extra cool.

Title: Long Dark Night
Comment: This album is one of the best things Nick Cave & The Bad Seeds have done. And I'm a fan of the older stuff. Anyway, enjoy, if you haven't heard. It's a nice time.

Title: NRA Back 2 School
Comment:
Looking at my Spotify Wrapped for last year, it's almost entirely songs that came out in the early 2000s because that's when my teenage brain stopped maturing. The only songs I could find in there from 2024 are off this album. 

I've submitted The Last Gang in another round, but they're definitely my favorite find from 2024. I got to see them live in November and they were so fucking good.

Title: Toilet
Comment: Saw this band play a new years gig last week. They're Korean and play very 90s ish stuff. Don't know why this song is called Toilet. Don't care either.

Title: BACKBONE
Comment: I saw Stormzy live in 2024 at a festival in Budapest and (as expected) he was INCREDIBLE and even more handsome in person. He played this song before it was officially released and the place absolutely erupted it was such a brilliant experience and the song is an absolute certified banger

Title: Trepanation
Artist(s): Hans Gruber and the Die Hards
Comment: Of all the shows I got to play this past year, these guys were hands down the most fun to be on the same bill with. After the show we traded copies of our respective LPs and theirs is now a standout in my record collection.

Title: Lithonia
Album: Bando Stone and The New World
Comment: I did think this started with "caught in the rain" at first instead of Cody LaRae

Title: Russian Roulette
Comment: Favorite song of 2024, and also released in 2024. I’ve been listening to this man since his initial angsty dubstep EP 15 years ago and his sadboiness has grown over the years with mine, not to mention my little sister and I finally became friends in our 20s when I dragged her to a show. This track hits all of those notes

Title: Everybody Hates The Cops
Artist(s): Sole, DJ Pain 1, Time, Lee Reed
Comment: Kinda cheating because this came out as a single in 2023 but it was an album track in 2024. My only other choices were an extremely depressing song or a seven minute-long song with two minutes of synth noise and I gotta learn to read the room here.

Title: The Stargate [Tablet I]
Comment: I know not traditionally a winning genre in the HT music league but I think I have to be true to myself on this one. I was not a Blood Incantation fan before hearing this album, but this weird combo of death metal and prog synth-y rock really got me. I also watched a documentary about the creation of this album and these guys are some hardcore fellow music nerds.

Title: I Know
Comment: Carrying the torch for the My Bloody Valentine sound (in the absence of any new material from MBV themselves in the last decade), but I think they bring something new and energetic to it as well. 149 monthly listeners, which should qualify them as being not super-obvious.

Title: Easy
Comment: Discovered this band just days before the end of 2023 and this track became one of my most listened songs in 2024.

Title: Dreams - 2004 Remaster
Comment: Scientifically speaking, Fleetwood Mac is the rare band that lies perfectly at the intersection of the three main types of music I like these days. If you don’t like Fleetwood Mac, I don’t even know what to tell you other than I guess you probably don’t like any of my three dominant taste elements. Also you probably have bad taste because this song is eternally popular for a reason.

Title: Panic Attack
Comment:
Borderline twee instrumentation. strained and nasally vocals, double-tracked. A sweeping, sentimental bridge followed by the instrumental being stripped down to bare bones. Lyrics about being desperately unwell and the strain it puts on interpersonal relationships, framed in part through the juxtaposition of genuine expressions of intense emotions with glaringly literal, simplistic descriptions of events and things.

But this wins over any mountain goats song that's all of those things bc trans

Title: kicks
Comment:
I love the lush analog-y synths at the start and also the plucky house-y synths that follow at 0.43 - I would've been happy with either all the way through, but having them alternate really hits my taste sweet spot.

I'm proud to say that I managed to slip this song into a Hard Times article once, not quite sure how. And also proud to say that I worked (remotely) on a song with Holly one time (although as she's a better producer / writer / singer than me she very much carried my amateur ass).

Title: The Mighty Heroes
Comment: Chose this simply because when I read the prompt this was the first thing that came to mind. Best not to overthink things

Title: The Man Who Sold The World - Live
Comment: If I am going to be genuine for a moment, my favourite artist of all time is David Bowie, and Nirvana sits proudly in the number 2 spot. Then everyone else is in a constant death battle for 3rd place. But therefore, this cover really does sum up my music taste, amalgamating my favs in a way that delighted me upon first discovery and thrills me every listen. Also taking into account my pure love for live music as well as my love for finding out who inspires my favourite artists

Title: Casablanca
Comment: I’m a sucker for the songs of our collective past. I adore songs that walk that fine line between “overly produced cheese” and “legit bangers”. As the years roll on, these beautifully cheesy songs from our past are getting co-opped by modern pop-culture (movie soundtracks, streamers, song samples, fucking ‘Stranger Things’, etc). The best songs for 2025 and beyond are the “dusty diamonds” like ‘Casablanca’ from Dane Donohue that scratch my vintage itch while still feeling bright and fresh.

Title: SPS
Comment: they yell and play the guitar loud what more could you want

Title: Shadow
Comment: I like music that's cinematic since I spend most of my listening time walking and daydreaming about the wonderful movies and TV shows I'll never make. I also like synthy stuff and this song is in one of my favourite scenes of the best show ever made: Twin Peaks The Return.

Title: A Better Place, a Better Time
Comment:
My personal music taste is not something that can be so easily defined. It’s vague, vast, irrational, and often questionable

Since I don’t have a choice though, here’s one that hits a bunch of the broader themes. Energetic build-up, vocalist giving their all, myriad of instruments, narratively beautiful or meaningful lyrics (extra points for the angst), and a performance that still somehow goes WAY harder live

Title: Byof
Comment: Let me put you on game real quick: A nobody bedroom producer from Minneapolis who I know next to nothing about. Their music combines hip hop, r&b, and some really jazzy instrumentals. Obscurity is a hallmark of my taste, but unlike half the shit I listen to, other people might actually enjoy this.

Title: Dead Bodies
Comment:
This album turns 25 this year, and it's still the first thing I play in the car on a road trip. I'll probably get shit for submitting Rancid, but I must be true to the theme of this round, which is that all of you are the ones who are wrong. 

Anyways, here's Lars frederiksen yelling for 2 minutes

Title: Zoom
Comment: I feel like I get typecast as liking more folksy music, but this song I think more defines the kinda music I love. Energetic, little funky, something you can dance and vibe too. Love it.

Title: Our Happiness is Guaranteed
Comment: I never really got into punk music, but I would listen to arty music made by punks. I love how this song wraps some dark, cynical lyrics in an approachable package.  Most of my music taste relies on a killer drummer and some form of electric instrument.

Title: The Beginning and the End
Comment:
I'm trying to avoid bands I've submitted too many times before, so here's something new:

Massachusetts-natives that pull influences from doom, metal, hardcore, sludge, and prog. A pretty perfect mix of things I like and one of the first bands that got me to even look at doom.

Title: Looking Down The Barrel Of A Gun
Comment: I love Beastie Boys. This album is perfect. But they describe my style because they play a bunch of different styles of music and have even introduced me to new music. I picked this specific tune because it’s a banger.

Title: Doorway
Comment:
Tunde Olaniran is a singer/rapper/activist/film-maker from Flint, Michigan with 12k monthly listeners. 

Yo-Yo Ma is a nearly 70 year-old, globally famous classical musician with 4.8 million listeners. 

If you're wondering how his cello playing ends up on this song - well, I'm not exactly sure, but as far as I can tell it does seem to be a real cameo rather than him being sampled.

Title: Mama
Comment: I was always very shocked to hear Liza Minnelli here. I honestly still don't know quite why this is the only song on the album with a feature and why it's her, but she does do it pretty well

Title: Pop Punk Band
Comment: The album cover kind of fucks this up for this round, but Matt skiba shows up in the bridge for this song. I think it was on a punk o Rama comp back in the day the first time I heard it and was caught of guard when he just suddenly takes charge of vocals.

Title: Knee Socks
Comment: Josh Homme from Queens of the Stone Age appears towards the end, which took me a while to place

Title: Goin' Back To Alabama
Comment: Yes. Yes that is Michael Jackson providing backup vocals on a Kenny Rogers song. Correct.

Title: All About It (feat. Ed Sheeran)
Comment: When this song dropped in 2014 Hoodie Allen was a relative nobody, so having Ed “86M Monthlies” Sheeran on your track was certainly a surprise. Today he’s got 1.7M and I’m certain half of that is from TikTok playlists. As an aside, ‘People Keep Talking’ is a great record that is a lot of fun

Title: Spacious Thoughts
Album: The Spirit of Apollo (10th Anniversary Special Edition)
Artist(s): N.A.S.A., Sam i, Tom Waits, Kool Keith
Comment: This album is chock full of guests, but the most puzzling (and in my books best) is Spacious Thoughts. Tom Waits on a hip hop track is a weird mix but I think it works. I don’t doubt that it didn’t for others though!

Title: One and Done
Album: Down in the Weeds, Where the World Once Was
Comment:
At around 1:46, you're thinking... that slap bass doesn't sound like Bright Eyes... this sounds like... like... Flea? No way, that would be too weird.

Well, guess what... it is Flea from the Red Hot Chili Peppers. Google it.

Title: My Yvonne
Comment: In 2007, Jack Peñate was recording his debut album and enlisted the help of an unknown 19 year old to provide backing vocals for him. She would end up forging her career on the chance he gave her and end up becoming the Vegas-residency performing artist we know today as Adele. She is not credited as a featured artist on the song; however, she is credited as a backing vocalist in the album's booklet. A slight genre break from some more usual music league subs but please enjoy

Title: Overkill
Comment:
You may recognize them as the guys that wrote the track that became the Scrubs theme song but wouldn’t know anything besides that

Well, 25 years ago, Colin Hay - the founding member of Men at Work - stumbled drunkenly into a studio he mistook as his own in the middle of a band recording a cover of a track HE wrote. Naturally, he hopped in for a hook but Lazlo Bane assumed he was just an oddly in-tune drifter so never credited him

(History might be off but he was initially uncredited)

Title: I'll Sing Your Song
Comment: I think the use of a "voice" in a surprising way counts here, and barbershop quartet Hatsune Miku fits into that category. Louie Zong's style is also usually all over the place, but this one especially felt out of place. Surprising all the way through

Title: Under Saturn's Shadow
Comment:
I didn't know back then that Davey Havok and Nick 13 had so many uncredited guest vocals on each other's albums that they might as well be considered uncredited backup singers. Which is odd because i listened to AFI and Tiger Army a lot in high school, but somehow, I never noticed?

Here's one where a Davey Havok is not even credited on a Tiger Army song, even though he's clearly the lead singer.

Title: Somebody's Watching Me
Comment: Not exactly a personal song, but a pretty famous example of the round, considering that it features an uncredited appearance by Michael Jackson(and two of his siblings, for God's sake).

Title: Dirty Computer (feat. Brian Wilson)
Comment: These round rules are confusing me a little, but what we know for sure the Brian Wilson presence on this song 1000% makes it even cooler and he is still ahead in overall historical fame and acclaim (for now)

Title: Character Development (Cold Start)
Comment: Band broke out late last year and they’re on a previously booked tour. They’re selling out tiny venues and the vibes are insane. This is their new album opener and their set opener. If you dig it, go.

Title: The Drunk
Comment: It took a lot of scrolling through my liked songs to find an exactly 200 second song. Gotta be one of my favorite albums, I seriously don't think I'll ever get tired of listening to any of the tracks.

Title: Waterlines
Comment: The life of an artist. Regret, decay, a fuzzy identity. Aging into nihilism and/or absurdism. Poetry on prescription bags. Wondering “what if” and imagining less lonely alternate realities. Cats help.

Title: Your Mother Wants To Know
Artist(s): Scrawl, Marcy Mays, Sue Harshe, Dana Marshall, Steve Albini
Comment: scrawl are a trio from columbus, ohio, active since 1985. this is a relatable song about family, and for some reason the audio engineer is listed as a collaborator (i guess because it's steve albini).

Title: Queen Bitch - 2015 Remaster
Comment: I found a few good contenders for this round but given the current state of the world, how about a song hailing the glory of Queens. And good luck stopping yourself from singing "bippity boppety hat".

Title: What a Fool Believes
Comment: “What a Fool Believes” by the Doobie Brothers slaps harder than your grandma's Thanksgiving yams. Michael McDonald’s voice could solve world peace. Honestly, 200 characters can’t capture its greatness!

Title: Incomplete

Title: All Star
Comment: I heard a story that the lead singer would take selfies with people, but if they put the L on their forehead, it was a no go. Anyway, that guy's dead now. RIP. He said some racist shit, right? Anyway.

Title: I THINK
Comment: I got into Tyler the Creator only recently and Igor has become a fave album of mine and ended up massively influencing the writing of my book. There’s a lot of jams on here but this one is 200 seconds

Title: eucharist
Comment: It sounds like one of those blurry nostalgic atmospheric soundscape youtube videos that are like “pov: ur walking past neon signs at the mall at night with mom in 1987” but then a bit colder, creepier

Title: I Hope Tomorrow is Like Today
Comment:
It's the Summer after Sophomore year, I'm driving home in the Chevy Malibu I just bought with 2 years of grocery stocking pay. I've just left my first real girlfriend's house after my first real kiss.



NOTE: it's listed as 3:20 in my playlist and on the CD, Spotify search be damned

Title: Swing Life Away
Comment:
The only song I could find that was 200 seconds was the song my wife and I chose for the first dance at our wedding. Sorry it wasn't some random Oi! band. I swear I wasn't going for sentimental.

- Mac

Title: Body Temp Spirits
Comment: Exactly 200 seconds/3:20. I forgot I was sitting on this song for a "you probably haven’t heard of them" round with only 71 monthly listeners, but it's a jam and it fits here, so enjoy! Screw Flanders

Title: Dawn
Comment: This is an “end of yoga class” staple song, so you can even close your eyes and trick your brain into thinking you’re lying there on the mat

Title: Where Will I Go
Comment: I have used this song a number of times for takeoffs. I don't get particularly anxious, but I can also never fall asleep on a plane, so good for settling in and just looking out a window (but I like an aisle seat, I'm in charge of this row!)

Title: Cristo Redentor - Remastered
Album: A New Perspective (Remastered / Rudy Van Gelder Edition)
Comment: Jazz calms me like no one’s business. This song really evokes some 70s energy, but man, does it soothe.

Title: A Night To Remember
Comment: An easy song to lose yourself in during takeoff, plus I feel even without the round theme, the whole song has an "on a plane" vibe to it

Title: Sleep Forever
Album: In the Mountain in the Cloud
Comment:
As a kiddo my family pretty exclusively did road trips, flying was a luxury. So when I went off to go to college on the other side of the country it became one of my new favorite things. Airports meant adventure, and I always had the perfect song queued up to maximize takeoff thrill. Window seat always, face glued to the sky. 

This track specifically reminds me of coming home for Xmas freshman year…

14 years later and I fly too much for work. Mostly I nap, in the window. Song still relevant.

Title: Rocket Man (I Think It's Going To Be A Long, Long Time)
Comment: Time to blast off, bitches.

Title: Nothing's Gonna Stop Us Now
Comment:
I’ve had a downloaded playlist for the last few years that used Enigmas “Return to Innocence” as the seed. “Return to Innocence” was the first song I discovered years ago that helped calm my SEVERE flight anxiety. 

Flash forward to today - I fly a ton for work now and my anxiety has improved. I’ve now listened to this one playlist HUNDREDS OF TIMES on countless flights. This Starship song is a current favorite from the list, and a good reminder that once takeoff starts… it ain’t stopping ✈️💕

Title: (I Just) Died In Your Arms
Comment: I'm terrified of flying and need music to distract me. For take off I need something that is long enough to play during the entirety of intense acceleration upwards (usually 3-4 minutes). I need a song with enough imagery from the lyrics that I can focus on, with enough going on musically to distract me, but not overly exciting so that it won't increase my heartrate even more. I need to cling to the person beside me. & if I did end up in a plane crash, I want my rescuers to enjoy my final listen

Title: Keep Moving On
Comment: I typically can't stand reggae, but The Aggrolites mix in enough funk and punk to get a hall pass from my music snobbery. This is one of their more chill songs. It's perfect for the next time you're trying to come down from a mile-high panic attack

Title: The Grocery
Album: A Black Mile To The Surface
Comment: A favorite album of mine that has a pretty chill vibe, even if the themes are a little (a lot) dark. Chose this because of the line “I don’t know where I’m going, but I’m going anyway”

Title: Destroy Everything You Touch
Comment: I don't get nervous flying so when I listen to music at take off, it's usually something high energy to get me hyped for a trip and also since my brain thinks in movie montages, I like to have something a bit soundtrack-y hence this choice

Title: Warmth of the Earth
Comment: Sione Teumohenga aka Lonelyspeck is an amazing Tongan-Australian producer/singer/guitarist. The rest of this EP, plus their more recent stuff, is louder and more energetic, but this song and their earlier stuff is more ambient and takeoff-friendly

Title: Dripfield
Comment:
Goose is more Dad Rock than I usually dig but it’s keeping my blood pressure down lately. Jam band vibes with better lyrics. Often compared to Vampire Weekend but I’m not cool enough to know Vampire Weekend.
A steady yet mellow groove that won’t panic your lizard brain as you live a life Icarus could only dream about. Long enough to reach cruising altitude. The production is deep so one can easily escape the terrors of a plane take-off by diving into this placid sonic pond.

Title: Hauntology
Comment:
702 monthly listeners
This whole album is worth a listen and it all sounds different, this is just my favorite.

Title: It's a Revolution
Comment:
107 monthly listeners

San Diego ska-punk

Title: Rust
Comment:
I honestly don't remember how I discovered these guys, but they're right up my alley with a pop-punky sound. 
1375 monthly listeners

Title: Hollowed Out
Comment:
In 2013 This Old Ghost combined indie folk, a little distortion, and these great, doubled male/female vocals—the kind you hear in classic country tunes. 

A whopping 78 monthly listeners feels criminal for how much I love this record.

Title: Talking A Hole In My Head
Comment: I have no particular connection to Norwich, England, but this is maybe the fifth Norwich band I've submitted to Music League for some reason. 39 monthly listeners, which is way less than they deserve.

Title: You
Comment: I rediscovered this song on an old playlist I made of bands that were playing at a festival I went to in 2018. It looks like Bad Bones haven't done anything since and sit pretty with 70 monthly listeners but this was a choon worth sharing

Title: Dirty Pictures
Comment: A few years ago I caught a free show by San Fermin while visiting my buddy in Brooklyn and we were blown away - this is the side project of their saxophonist, and it’s awesome.

Title: Bathed In Red
Comment: shoegazey, sort of noisy, great layered guitars. I wish they had more songs! 52 listeners, safely below the max.
659 listeners. Shame cos they're a funky little Korean group

Title: Daniel Day Lewis
Album: Give Yourself a Kiss for Me
Comment: A silly and sweet little song about Hollywood admiration/obsession from an artist with only 244 monthly listeners.

Title: Pagoda City Ripper
Album: Fast Times at Hex County High
Comment: 15 monthly listeners

Title: Saints At The Gates
Comment: A Toronto indie. Dig this tune. Criminally low monthly listeners

Title: You Did What You Had to Do
Comment: Local group featuring a homie of mine. I was jamming this at work today.  I keep mistaking for a bigger artist when it’s stuck in my head. It has a synthy sound combined with folk punk vibes. Shout out to San Antonio, this city sucks but there’s some good art here. And fuck the Alamo. (Can we say “fuck” on here?)
